<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-267-130  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 267 130.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 26 1990 v4 n8 p8(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AF mulls condensed Mission Planning. (the Air Force Tactical AirForces Advanced Mission Planning System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Air Force is reconsidering its decision to spend $100 millionto develop prototype tactical mission planning systems for itstactical fighter aircraft under the Tactical Air Forces AdvancedMission Planning System (TAFAMPS).andP;  TAFAMPS was intendedoriginally to include automatic feeds of near-real-timeintelligence, weather and other data required by air crews forpremission planning, mission rehearsal and post-mission review.andO;New Defense Department budget directives and the proposedrestructuring of Pentagon procurement procedures have caused achange in TAFAMPS plans, including broadening the scope of thehardware and software to include the Strategic Air Command and theMilitary Airlift Command in addition to the Tactical Air Command.andO;Spending on the prototype phase will be cut in half from theoriginal $100 million estimate despite the centralization plans; adual award will be made for an 18-month prototype development withproduction options.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryAircraftPrototypePlanningCommand and Control SystemsDefense ContractsWeaponsGovernment ContractsUnited States. Air Force. Tactical Air Command.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>